<paper id="1648919568"><title>On the zone of a surface in a hyperplane arrangement</title><year>1991</year><authors><author org="" id="2067038581">Boris Aronov</author><author org="New-York University &gt;  &gt;  &gt;  &gt;" id="2154115838">Micha Sharir</author></authors><n_citation>11</n_citation><doc_type>Conference</doc_type><references><reference>1511715036</reference><reference>1984529618</reference><reference>2017345057</reference><reference>2022266599</reference><reference>2156316434</reference><reference>2404213258</reference></references><venue id="1149998698" type="C">Workshop on Algorithms and Data Structures</venue><doi>10.1007/BFb0028245</doi><keywords><keyword weight="0.44901">Binary logarithm</keyword><keyword weight="0.46567">Discrete mathematics</keyword><keyword weight="0.46963">Combinatorics</keyword><keyword weight="0.57669">Convex body</keyword><keyword weight="0.56266">Algebraic surface</keyword><keyword weight="0.49753">Half-space</keyword><keyword weight="0.51731">Hyperplane</keyword><keyword weight="0.60915">Vertex enumeration problem</keyword><keyword weight="0.40591">Mathematics</keyword><keyword weight="0.43647">Bounding overwatch</keyword></keywords><publisher>Springer, Berlin, Heidelberg</publisher><abstract>Let H be a collection of n hyperplanes in ℝ d , let A denote the arrangement of H, and let σ be a (d - 1)-dimensional algebraic surface of low degree, or the boundary of a convex body in ℝd. The zone of σ in A is the collection of cells of A crossed by σ. We show that the total number of faces bounding the cells of the zone of σ is O(nd−1 log n).</abstract></paper>